r post-doctoral fellowship is an extension of doctoral work concerned with the place of genetic knowledge in understanding and managing common diseases.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The doctoral research provides an empirical investigation of the geneticisation thesis, focussing on familial hypercholesterolaemia (FH), a treatable hereditary cholesterol condition associated with high rates of CHD. It asks how much and in what ways FH and CHD are constructed as genetic, focusing particularly on the constructions of professionals involved with HEART UK, the main UK health charity involved with inherited lipid disorders and cholesterol, and on the constructions of patients with FH. The research challenges the geneticisation thesis in a number of important respects, suggesting that FH is not understood or managed within a strong genetic frame. Furthermore, neither professionals involved with HEART UK, nor patients with FH provided or contributed to more general geneticised accounts of CHD.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The aims of the fellowship are to disseminate the findings to social science and medical audiences through publication and conference presentation, and to undertake limited further research and develop research proposals concerned with the emergence of a genomic model of CHD in biomedical discourses and broadening the findings on patient constructions of FH and raised cholesterol.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>65354</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E6F3CD0C-6D5F-42CE-8B29-BBED9B5592D2</gtr:id><gtr:title>A genetic future for coronary heart disease?</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Sociology of health &amp; illness</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/a3c3f07ae14f0b351b41af3c4698c05b"><gtr:id>a3c3f07ae14f0b351b41af3c4698c05b</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Weiner K</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0141-9889</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>pm_53cbf7ebf7ef42e84</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>C8A34FCA-FEB7-4FF8-87DD-C6A6B3DF693C</gtr:id><gtr:title>Patients' understandings and experiences of familial hypercholesterolemia.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Community genetics</gtr: